Predicting Absenteeism - Group Assignment 1
¶

In this machine learning project, we use employee records in a two-week period to predict whether or not he/she would be absent for 5 days or more in the next two-week period. This is the output variable. The absentee data from six periods are observed: the first and second halves of June, August and October 2018. It can be inferred from our prediction models, that an employee’s interactions with his/her colleagues and satisfaction during one period may affect his/her attendance in the immediate next period.

Fist we explore the evolution of the number of comments. In order to get a better picture of how comments evolved, we plot the overall comment figures month-on-month. A daily plot would be too granular in order to observe differences in movement. It can be noted that the peak in the number of mothly comments was in the initial period (over 500 comments), while subsequently the number of monhtly comments dropped sharply (below 200) and maintained levels below 300 month on month, until the end of the period. The initial spike may be because employees were enthsuastic about using the platform when it was launched.

1.4 Whether or not an employee is absent¶

The scatter plot below shows the distribution of start and end dates of each case of absenteeism. The data is fractured into 3 parts: cases that start and end within June 2018, August 2018 and October 2018.

In [30]:
absentees['from'] = pd.to_datetime(absentees['from'], format="%m/%d/%y %H:%M")
absentees['to'] = pd.to_datetime(absentees['to'], format="%m/%d/%y %H:%M")

plt.scatter(absentees['from'],absentees['to'])
plt.grid()
plt.xlabel('Start date')
plt.ylabel('End date')
Out[30]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'End date')

Include new column 'length', which shows the length of each case of being absent. Add one day to the each entry in the length column, as it appears that the 'from' column shows the first day that the employee took leave, and the 'to' column shows the last day that the employee that he/she took leave.

In [91]:
absentees['length'] = absentees['to'] - absentees['from']
absentees['length'] = absentees['length'] + timedelta(days=1)
absentees['length'] = [int(x.days) for x in absentees['length']]

We check the maximum length of absence among all employees, on any one occasion. We find that the maximum length of absence is 31 days.

In [92]:
print(absentees["length"].max())

31

The stacked bar chart below shows the lengths (in days) of each case of absenteeism. Most instances identifed are of absenteeism lasting 31 days (26 times employees were absent for 31 days). Also, 16 instances of absenteeism lasting 31 days were identifed. These are instances of longer term absenteeism. Simiarly we note that a siginificant number of instances relate to short term absenteeism (14 instances when employees were absent for 2 days and 10 instances when employees were absent for 1 day). We note that these lenghts of absenteeism relate to individual instances of absenteeism. Much fewer instances of absenteeism between 3 and 29 days have been identified, ranging from 1 to maximum 6 instances.

"Common sickness or accident not related to the job" is the reason given by most absent employees. All cases of "long term sick leave" last for 28 days or above.

Part 2: Model construction and evaluation¶

2.1 Creating the input and output variables¶

Here are the input and output variables for the construction of the machine learning models.

Output variable: Whether an employee was absent for 5 days or more during the current 2-week period (i.e. first and second halves of June, August and October 2018)

Input variables relate to the 2-week period preceding each of the periods in the output variable

  1. Likes and dislikes received
  2. No. of comments made
  3. Likes and dislikes given
  4. Total number of votes
  5. Average vote value (if no votes were cast, we consider it to be a neutral score of 2.5 on a 1-4 scale)
  6. Number of “high” votes (a score of 3-4) and “low” votes (1-2)

We define a case of absenteeism as an employee who is absent for 5 days or more within a 2-week period. As such, an employee can be an absentee in one period and not be one in another period, depending on the number of days of absence during that period.

This definition of absenteeism may be ideal for this task for a few reasons:

  1. There are many legitimate reasons for an employee to be absent which do not cause concern for the company, especially if he/she is only absent for several days within half a month. He/she may be genuinely ill, and require several days for recovery. Therefore, short absences are a common and even inevitable phenomenon that need not be reduced. However, if an employee is absent for more than 5 days in 2 weeks, the company should pay closer attention, as it may be a pattern of behaviour that significantly affects productivity if widespread among employees.

  2. Cases of absenteeism in the dataset are fragmented as 3 distinct timeframes: June, August and October, which we further break in half. Suppose an employee is only absent for many days in the first half of June, and has not been absent since. First, we would be unfair and inaccurate to label this employee as an absentee permanently, since that behaviour was not consistent throughout June to October. Next, for the sake of prediction, it would make more sense to observe his/her behaviour immediately before that period, as possible relevant features to predict absenteeism in the current period. The worse alternative is averaging out the features and actions of an employee throughout all available time (2017-2019), which would render the prediction model imprecise.

In [3]:
comments['commentDate'] = pd.to_datetime(comments['commentDate'], format="%Y-%m-%d %H:%M")
interactions['actionDate'] = pd.to_datetime(interactions['actionDate'], format="%Y-%m-%d %H:%M")
votes["voteDate"] = pd.to_datetime(votes["voteDate"], format="%Y-%m-%d %H:%M")
absentees['from'] = pd.to_datetime(absentees['from'], format="%m/%d/%y %H:%M")
absentees['to'] = pd.to_datetime(absentees['to'], format="%m/%d/%y %H:%M")
quit['deletedOn'] = pd.to_datetime(quit['deletedOn'], format="%m/%d/%y %H:%M")

We observe 6 two-week periods for our analysis of absentee cases, which are the first half and the second half of June, August and October 2018 respectively. These are the "current periods" of our output variable.
For our input variables, we also observe 6 two-week periods, which are the two-week period immediately preceding each of the "current periods" in our output variables, i.e. second half of May, first half of June, second half of July, first half of August, second half of September and first half of October.

In [5]:
all_data = pd.DataFrame()

for i in range(len(start_date_in)):
    received = comments[(comments['commentDate'] >= start_date_in[i]) & (comments['commentDate'] <= end_date_in[i])]
    # Total dislikes received in comments made by the employee 
    dis_received = received.groupby('employee')['dislikes'].sum()
    
    # Total likes received in comments made by the employee
    like_received = received.groupby('employee')['likes'].sum()
    
    # No. of comments made by the employee
    comment_count = received.groupby('employee')['commentId'].count()
    
    given = interactions[(interactions['actionDate'] >= start_date_in[i]) & (interactions['actionDate'] <= end_date_in[i])]
    
    # Total dislikes given by the employee
    dis_given = given.groupby('employee')['interaction'].apply(lambda x: (x == -1).sum())
    
    # Total likes given by the employee
    like_given = given.groupby('employee')['interaction'].apply(lambda x: (x == 1).sum())
    
    vote = votes[(votes['voteDate'] >= start_date_in[i]) & (votes['voteDate'] <= end_date_in[i])]
    
    # Average vote value of the employee
    avg_vote = vote.groupby('employee')['vote'].mean()
    avg_vote = avg_vote.rename('a')
    
    # No. of votes made by the employee
    vote_count = vote.groupby('employee')['vote'].count()
    vote_count = vote_count.rename('b')
    
    # No. of high-scoring votes (3 or 4)
    high_vote = vote.groupby('employee')['vote'].apply(lambda x: (x >= 3).sum())
    high_vote = high_vote.rename('c')
    
    # No. of low-scoring votes (1 or 2)
    low_vote = vote.groupby('employee')['vote'].apply(lambda x: (x <= 2).sum())
    low_vote = low_vote.rename('d')
    
    # List of employees who were absent during the current period 
    absent = absentees[((absentees['from'] >= start_date_out[i]) & (absentees['from'] <= end_date_out[i]))|
                      ((absentees['to'] >= start_date_out[i]) & (absentees['to'] <= end_date_out[i]))]
    absent = absent.reset_index(drop=True)
    
    # Length of absence (if total days of absence during 2-week period >= 5, then count as absentee)
    len_list = []
    for k in range(len(absent)):
        if absent['from'][k] < start_date_out[i]:
            len_list.append(absent['to'][k] - start_date_out[i] + timedelta(days = 1))
        elif absent['to'][k] > end_date_out[i]:
            len_list.append(end_date_out[i] - absent['from'][k])
        else: 
            len_list.append(absent['to'][k] - absent['from'][k] + timedelta(days = 1))
    
    absent['length'] = len_list
    
    dat = pd.DataFrame()
    dat = absent.groupby('employee')['length'].sum().to_frame()
    dat = dat.rename_axis('employee').reset_index()
    dat['length'] = [x.round(freq = 'D').days for x in dat['length']]
    
    alist = []
    for j in range(len(dat.length)):
        if dat.length[j] >= 5: 
            alist.append(1)
        else:
            alist.append(0)
    dat['absent'] = alist
    
        
    quit_list = quit.employee[quit['deletedOn'] < start_date_out[i]].to_list() 
    all_emp = quit['employee'].unique()
    cur_emp = pd.DataFrame()
    cur_emp['employee'] = [x for x in all_emp if x not in quit_list]
    
    dat = pd.merge(cur_emp, dat, on='employee', how='left').fillna(0)
    
    dat = pd.merge(dat, dis_received, on='employee', how='left').fillna(0)
    dat = pd.merge(dat, like_received, on='employee', how='left').fillna(0)
    dat = pd.merge(dat, comment_count, on='employee', how='left').fillna(0)  
    dat = pd.merge(dat, dis_given, on='employee', how='left').fillna(0)
    dat = pd.merge(dat, like_given, on='employee', how='left').fillna(0)
    dat = pd.merge(dat, high_vote, on='employee', how='left').fillna(0)
    dat = pd.merge(dat, low_vote, on='employee', how='left').fillna(0)
    # If the employee did not vote during the period, the default average vote value a neutral score of 2.5.
    dat = pd.merge(dat, avg_vote, on='employee', how='left').fillna(2.5)
    dat = pd.merge(dat, vote_count, on='employee', how='left').fillna(0)    
    
    # Period 0 = First half of June; Period 1 = Second half of June; Period 2 = First half of August...
    dat['period'] = i
    
    dat.columns = ['employee','length','absent','dis_received','like_received','comment_count','dis_given','like_given',
                  'high_vote','low_vote','avg_vote','vote_count','period']
    all_data = pd.concat([all_data,dat])

2.3 Decision tree¶

We construct a decision tree as follows.
From the tree below, we see that "likes received" forms the first split: if total likes received is lower than 0.5 (i.e. equals zero), then the case is classified as "absentee", otherwise, classify as "non-absentee". "Vote count" forms the second split: if the total vote count is lower than 3.35, then classify as "non-absentee", otherwise, classify as "absentee".

SVM may not be the ideal model for this dataset, as the two classes overlap for various input variables. As shown in k-means clustering in the next part, the average value of the absentee cluster’s likes and dislikes received, as well as likes and dislikes given, are caught between Clusters 0 and 1. Clusters 0 and 1 are both large non-absentee clusters.

2.5 KNN - using K-fold cross validation¶

We also try using using the K-nearest neighbours algorithm to construct our prediction model, with k = any odd number between 1 and 99. In order to minimise overfitting, cross validation is performed on the dataset when constructing the models. To address the imbalance of classes in our data, Stratified K Fold is used to perform the splits in cross validation: each set contains approximately the same percentage of samples of each target class as the complete set.

Unfortunately, since the k-NN algorithm is based on majority voting for classification, cases from the majority class tend to dominate the predictions. Therefore, the sensitivity scores for all values of k are too low to be used for prediction of absenteeism.

In [20]:
# dependent and independent variables split
X = all_data.iloc[:,3:12]
y = all_data.iloc[:,2]
In [21]:
# normalize the data
scaler = StandardScaler()
X = scaler.fit_transform(X)
In [22]:
k_range = range(1, 100 ,2)
k_scores = []

for k in k_range:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)
    accuracy = cross_val_score(knn, X, y, cv = skf, scoring = 'accuracy')
    sensitivity = cross_val_score(knn, X, y, cv = skf, scoring = 'recall')
    k_scores.append({
        'k': k,
        'accuracy': accuracy.mean(),
        'sensitivity': sensitivity.mean(),
        'average': (accuracy.mean() + sensitivity.mean())/2
    })

Part 3: K means clustering (to categorise different types of employees)¶

We use K-means clustering to categorise different types of employees, in order to have a more nuanced picture of the behavioural patterns of employees. Same as our analysis above, each row represents an employee's behaviour during a particular period; there are multiple time periods being observed.

In [282]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
clusterdata = all_data.iloc[:,[0,1,3,4,5,6,7,8,9,10,11]].set_index('employee')
clusterdata.iloc[:,:] = scaler.fit_transform(clusterdata.iloc[:,:].to_numpy())
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=5, random_state=42).fit(clusterdata)
all_data['cluster'] = kmeans.labels_

After normalising the data, we categorised employee cases into 5 clusters, using k-means clustering. The most important cluster is Cluster 4, which singles out most of the absentee cases, since their average absent length (14.74 days) is significantly higher than other clusters, which are only absent for less than 0.1 days in a 2-week period on average.

It is notable that the non-absentee cases have a large variation of their level of engagement, happiness level, and in extension, level of motivation amongst themselves.

Cluster 0 has the largest number of cases, with a population of 1206. Its defining feature is its lack of engagement on the company’s online platforms. On average, they receive less than 1 dislike and 1 like, and give less than 1 dislike and 1 like in a 2-week period. These employees are the “silent majority” who rarely express themselves yet generally have good attendance.

Cluster 1 is also populous, with 793 cases. Their defining characteristic is that they represent the happiest employees in the company (with an average vote score of 3.38), and frequently express this sentiment with high votes (voting 11.47 times in 2 weeks).

Cluster 2 is the unhappy minority, with 335 cases. They have the lowest average vote score of 1.56.

Cluster 3 is a very small vocal minority, which only consists of a few employees who receive a lot of attention, interact very frequently, and are as unhappy as Cluster 2.

We can compare the absentee cluster with these 4 other clusters. The absentees’ level of engagement is relatively low: they receive less like and dislikes, give less likes and dislikes, and comment less frequently than all other Clusters except the "silent majority" cluster. However, on average, Cluster 4 votes around 5 times as frequently as the "silent majority". They cast significantly more low votes than Clusters 0 and 1 (both clusters collectively make up 82% of all cases). This echoes our observations in supervised learning models that absentees have low engagement with other employees, and regularly state their dissatisfaction through votes.
